[normal]remain
[normal] dissatisfied.  They feel that there is a fundamental flaw still in the way that the Ombudsman’s office reviews decision-making.  I suppose the obvious answer is, do you not think that that review process, instead of being done within the office, should be done externally?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]:[bold] 
[normal] 
[normal]Picking up that question specifically, we are the only ombudsman service with a dedicated team, with a separate reporting line and that uses external reviewers for reviews of our decisions.  We are the only ombudsman service that has those three things in place.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q199 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Greg Mulholland[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]In the 
[normal]UK
[normal]?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]As far as I know, yes.  Yes, we are definitely the only ombudsman service among the main public ombudsman services and the large private sector ones who have any external reviewers for reviews of decisions.  Some of them will use external people to consider service complaints—whether someone was rude, messing up the computer, those kinds of complaints—but on reviewing decisions we are the only ombudsman service that has external reviewers.
[normal]  
[normal]We use external reviewers for about 10% to 15% of our cases, and there is very little difference in the uphold rates for internal and external reviews.  Does that answer your question?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q200 [bold]&#xa0; 
