[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q225 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]Okay.  To 
[normal]what
[normal] extent would a single portal be a useful innovation?  How realistic a prospect is one?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]There are probably several, rather than just one.  This will need thinking through in terms of any recommendations the Committee may want to make in relation to a single portal.  For example, with the EU directive on alternative dispute resolution there is a requirement for a digital platform for complaints, and this may speed up Ombudsman Service collaboration on a shared portal, which could go across public and private sector, for example.  In health, NHS England has started a pilot called Care Connect with the aim of doing exactly that for health, so that someone can 
[normal]ring
[normal] them up and say, “What do I do?  I want to complain about X,” and, depending upon where they are—like whether this is the first time they have raised it or they have already tried to raise it with the hospital and they have got fed up—Care
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Connect will then refer them to the right place.  It seems particularly relevant in health because, as you know, health is a very regulated sector.  Sometimes people will think, “I want this clinician struck off,” and so they want the General Medical Council or the Nursing and Midwifery Council, to say, “I want to give you some intelligence about a particular clinician,” and so that might be the right referral.  It might be they want to do that but they also want someone to address their complaint, so they need to go both to the regulator and to ourselves as an ombudsman service, so something specific for health makes sense.
[normal]For the 
[normal]UK
[normal] services—the central Government Departments and agencies—at the moment there has been very little appetite, but I am quite concerned that we do not get many complaints about 
[normal]UK
[normal] services coming from 
[normal]Scotland
[normal], 
[normal]Wales
[normal] and 
[normal]Northern
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ireland
[normal].  Therefore, another portal to explore would be whether the public ombudsman services in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] could do something jointly to make it easier for people to access the 
[normal]UK
[normal] bit of our jurisdiction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q226 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]Would it be difficult to implement a successful complaints portal?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]I think it is too early, in a sense, to respond to your question, Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Turner, because there are a number of options, and we probably need to do some research with consumers to understand how they think about making a complaint and how they think about using an ombudsman service, to know what the best configuration is and then look at those practical issues.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q227 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]What
[normal] 
[normal]benefits do you think there are to having a single public services ombudsman?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]There are a number of benefits to rationalising the public ombudsman service landscape.  One is ease of access for the consumer.  For example, at the moment, if you have a complaint about something that has happened in a care home, you probably will not even know if that is something that is provided by the NHS or by the care home funded by the local authority or privately.  That is a perfect example of where it is going to be much easier if everything is in one place.  
[normal]Whatever is done would need to be coherent for the service providers.  For example, it would not make sense to have all the different national 
[normal]UK
[normal] ombudsmen services considering complaints about 
[normal]UK
[normal] services within each nation, because you would then potentially have inconsistent decisions by different ombudsman services.  
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]That is an extremely important point, and I had not really thought about that.
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]In looking at how we can make this better for the consumer, we also need to look at comprehensive coverage.  At the moment, we have our two schemes, health and 
[normal]UK
[normal] services, we have the Local Government Ombudsman, we have the Housing Ombudsman, but education at the moment is a bit missing.  Therefore, defining this as something that is about all public services rather than listing which services are in or out, for the public it is everything that is publicly funded—back to your point about private providers of public services as well. 
[normal]Whatever we do needs to reflect the devolution settlement.  We have great comprehensive services in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal], 
[normal]Wales
[normal] and 
[normal]Northern
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ireland
[normal] that do that linking of the local and the national and we definitely need that for 
[normal]England
[normal].  The bit that is probably more difficult to work through is the 
[normal]UK
[normal] bit of our jurisdiction, but one thing to consider in our current devolution settlement is that 
[normal]Westminster
[normal] deals with 
[normal]UK
[normal] and 
[normal]England
[normal].  Whatever we do needs to meet that principle of fitting with the current democratic and devolution settlement.
[normal]The last principle that would need to apply is value for money.  Let us have this reduce the number of organisations, because it will cost less money.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q228 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Can I just ask about what Robert
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hazell
[normal] calls the devolution wrinkle?  That to have an 
[normal]England
[normal] public service ombudsman would clearly mirror what happens in 
[normal]Northern
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ireland
[normal], 
[normal]Scotland
[normal] and 
[normal]Wales
[normal], but of course to duplicate your role in 
[normal]England
[normal] would seem to be rather otiose.  How would you address the devolution wrinkle?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]I suppose that is partly why I laid out those principles, because rather than having a solution on a plate, this would need working through, and if those six principles were met those would be good tests for any designs that the Committee may consider.  You 
[normal]are absolutely right: we need an English public ombudsman service, so that you get the national and local integrated in how we deal with complaints.  We need to think creatively about the 
[normal]UK
[normal] part of it.  I am not making a recommendation here, but there are some ideas for consideration on how we might meet those principles.  For example, in a sense a bit like we are, you could have two schemes but delivered by one organisation, so you could have a 
[normal]UK
[normal] scheme and an 
[normal]England
[normal] scheme.  They are separate schemes recognising the devolution wrinkle, if you like.  You could have the virtual access—the portal idea of how we could get more complaints for the UK services from Scotland, Wales and Northern
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ireland, which are very, very low at the moment, and so whether there is some kind of portal across all the public ombudsman services to bring that in.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q229 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Do you think it would be possible to get, say, the Scotland Ombudsman to resolve 
[normal]UK
[normal] questions on your behalf according to your policies, or is that too complicated?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]That would not meet two of the principles that I have outlined.  It would not meet the principle about the coherence for the service provider, as you have already noted, because you could get inconsistent decisions between different ombudsman services.  The other one is it may be a devolution wrinkle but the devolution settlement in terms of accountability is that 
[normal]Westminster
[normal] does cover both the 
[normal]UK
[normal] and 
[normal]England
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q230 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Some of us did warn about these wrinkles before the devolution settlement—or 
[normal]unsettlement
[normal]—was imposed.
[normal]  
[normal]Could the Scotland Ombudsman act as a gateway to your service, so all complaints go through the Scotland Ombudsman, and they decide whether it is a 
[normal]UK
[normal] matter or a Scottish matter?
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]That is exactly the kind of creativity we need on this question
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q231 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Kelvin [bold]Hopkins[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]I wanted to intervene a little earlier about the question of scale, because 
[normal]England
[normal] is 10
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]times the size of 
[normal]Scotland
[normal] and more than that of 
[normal]Northern
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ireland
[normal] and 
[normal]Wales
[normal].  Scale is significant in this if you are going to have relationships with all the organisations.  Devolution possibly to regions might be a consideration.
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]We have a Financial Ombudsman Service that deals with a million contacts a year, so I do not think scale has to be an issue at all
[normal].  
[normal]In terms of thinking specifically about the regional ombudsman, one of the challenges there and thinking of it from the customer perspective is that in 
[normal]England
[normal] we do not have regional services.  It has to be local or national and, as we know, phone and web are both local and global now, so in terms of access I do not think you need regional ombudsmen.  
[normal]In terms of governance, I would not recommend having different ombudsmen in regions.  We have just seen the Robert
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Gordon review of the governance arrangements for the Local Government Ombudsman, which is recommending moving from three ombudsmen in different parts of the country to one, exactly because of the need to have greater consistency, greater clarity of leadership and better governance.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q232 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]If 
[normal]the
[normal] Financial Ombudsman can deal with a million, is that because it is a slightly easier job than your job?
[normal]  
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Good question
[normal].  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]I think we all have jobs that are easy and difficult in different ways.  It is apples and pears; I do not think you can compare
[normal].  
[normal]I was just making the simpler point and, indeed, for ourselves, because we want to accept more cases for investigation and we want to deliver for more people, we are looking at becoming a much higher
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]volume
[normal] organisation.
[normal]Mr Turner[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]It would be nice to have some evidence of the size
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q233 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]We will write you a note about that.  Can we move on briefly to the last topic, which is about our relationship
[normal]?  
[normal]We are pushing over the time boundary, and I am craving the indulgence of colleagues just to do this very important piece.  What do you think is wrong with our relationship?  I would like to dwell on what is good about our relationship, but we must concentrate on the bad points.
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]We are talking about the two relationships, are we not?  We are talking about one in relation to us being accountable to Parliament for our service, as indeed other independent organisations are.  The other is how Parliament can use our services to hold Government services to account.  It is probably that latter one where there is an opportunity for Parliament and us working together to have more impact for the public.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q234 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]When
[normal] you produce a health service report, for example, what do you do in order to make sure that the Health Committee takes up the issue?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: Can I beg your indulgence and take it a step back? 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Take a step back if you are quick.
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]The opportunity to have greater impact, because this Committee has been very diligent over the years at taking our reports where a Government body has failed to accept our recommendations for action.  Whether it was Equitable
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Life or pensions or rural payment, this Committee has done a fantastic job, and that is why we have nearly 100% compliance with our recommendations, because people know if they say, “No”, we come to you and you will hold a hearing.
[normal]Where there is the opportunity for greater impact is holding Government to account for action on service
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]wide
[normal] or system
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]wide
[normal] changes as we begin to do more of that.  The examples would be on sepsis, on midwifery, on the Victims’ Code—a range of issues.  That is where there is scope for Parliament to be holding to account.  
[normal]On your question specifically about what we do to send to the Health Committee, we need to remember what the standing orders are here.  This Committee is the inheritor of the Parliamentary Commissioner for Administration—my job—and its standing orders are to examine reports of PHSO.  That is not in the standing orders of any of the subject Select Committees.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q235 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]If we were to enlarge your impact or to recommend the House to enlarge your impact, what effect do you think it would have if we recommended that in fact every Departmental Select Committee should have in its standing orders to receive reports from you relevant to their remit and respond to them?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]There are a number of options that could be considered, and that is absolutely one of them, where PASC retains the responsibility that it has taken on itself where we are held to account and individual Select Committees take on the scrutiny of service failures.  That is one option.  
[normal]It is also worth looking at what this Committee recommended in 2007, where it accepted, with the dual roles of us being held to account and helping you hold services to account, that they were best done by separate Committees.  In fact, they recommended an Officer of the House Commission, a bit like the Public Accounts Commission, for the accountability, then a bit like PASC for helping scrutinise services.  
[normal]There are probably three options that the Committee might wish to consider.  One is the one you have suggested of PASC retaining the scrutiny role and other Select Committees taking on the service-failure role.  Another is this Officer of the House Commission to take the accountability role and PASC to take the role of scrutinising service failure.  Short of legislation, there might also be a short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term solution to this one Committee doing both roles, which it is recognised there is a tension there.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q236 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Can you just explain why there is a tension there, and why you feel that that is an unsatisfactory role 
[normal]for
[normal] us, both receiving your reports and scrutinising your performance?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]You raised one earlier, which is accusations of 
[normal]cosying
[normal] up and collaboration between my office and this Committee
[normal].  
[normal]In the session with Oliver
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Letwin
[normal], I think you said that it inhibits the relationship with us in supporting you in holding services to account.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q237 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]I am bound to 
[normal]agree
[normal] with that, but what do you feel
[normal]?  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: I
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]hink that is right.  There have been things where we would have been able to help you with other inquiries because of evidence from our casework, which there has been an inhibition to do because you are also holding us to account
[normal].  
[normal]I just think it is better for all if it is more transparent and if the scrutiny of the office is separated from the work we do together.  It is what was recognised with the establishment of the National Audit Office with the two bodies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q238 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]If we start really thinking about your governance arrangements, you are the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman.  As an individual, you are chairman and chief executive of your organisation, in effect
[normal].  
[normal]These days we usually default to a very different type of governance arrangement 
[normal]with
[normal] a non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]executive
[normal] chairman or a part
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time chairman and a board of non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]executives
[normal] who appoint the chief executive.  What do you feel about your inherited legislative governance arrangements and how do you feel that should change?
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]The model you have just outlined is the right kind of model for robust governance and leadership of an organisation in the 21st
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]century.  We have tried to make a step towards that, as I said right at the beginning, where we have established a unitary board of executives and non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]executives
[normal], which I chair.  That was part of why we appointed Helen
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hughes as the Chief Operating Officer, to lead the organisation.  If you are proposing that there is a much more comprehensive public ombudsman service or services for the 
[normal]UK
[normal] and 
[normal]England
[normal], all the way from local to national to 
[normal]UK
[normal], then that would be a perfect opportunity to look at governance arrangements afresh.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q239 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] How 
[normal]would that work: the Ombudsman would be the chairman or the Ombudsman would be the chief executive
[normal]?  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]I think the Ombudsman would be the chief executive.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q240 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Who
[normal] would appoint the Ombudsman?
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]Indeed, if you need a named ombudsman.  If you look at the model of the Legal Ombudsman Service and the Financial Ombudsman Service, the Financial Ombudsman Service has 80
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]named ombudsmen.  We provide a service, and so the whole issue of personal jurisdiction is quite anachronistic and old-fashioned.
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]A bit Victorian.
[normal]  
[normal]Dame Julie Mellor[bold]: 
[normal]Yes, and so I think it would be much better for Parliament to appoint the chair of a public ombudsman service, the chair and Parliament together appoint the board and, as you suggest, the board then appoints the chief executive.  One of the things that does is it provides a barrier for the person who is leading the organisation to guarantee the independence of the office.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q241 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
